Q: Is it safe to use NativeMemory.Copy for overlapping regions of memory? A: <p>This method is <a href="https://github.com/dotnet/dotnet/blob/b0f34d51fccc69fd334253924abd8d6853fad7aa/src/runtime/src/libraries/System.Private.CoreLib/src/System/Runtime/InteropServices/NativeMemory.cs#L62" rel="nofollow noreferrer">currently implemented as</a> <code>memmove</code>:</p>
<pre><code>[CLSCompliant(false)]
public static void Copy(void* source, void* destination, nuint byteCount)
{
    SpanHelpers.Memmove(ref *(byte*)destination, ref *(byte*)source, byteCount);
}
</code></pre>
<p>But that's an implementation detail, as it's not documented as such, so that would be unsafe, as a different implementation could leave you with undefined behaviour.</p>
<p>Instead, you can just use <a href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.buffer.memorycopy#system-buffer-memorycopy(system-void*-system-void*-system-int64-system-int64)" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><code>Buffer.MemoryCopy</code></a>, which has the following remarks:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>If some regions of the source area and the destination overlap, the function ensures that the original source bytes in the overlapping region are copied before being overwritten.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>So it <em>is</em> safe in that case, and should be forever.</p>
